The seabed hides a little-known world so far, rich in natural resources.
There are oil, minerals and other mineral resources, but also living organisms unknown at the moment, which may hold the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A background larger than the hard ground
The coastal states have now begun to aspire vehemently to new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they are indeed using their rights, which they agreed on in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers off the coast of the given country.
The latter may, according to the convention, be entitled exclusively to all the resources of the continental shelf.
For simplicity, the continental shelf is the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which constitutes a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic yone," explains Mikulka.
The request that the country in question submits to the Commission for the Establishment of the Outer Borders of the Continental Shelf must be supported by extensive scientific-technical documentation, based on many costly surveys and metrology.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
So far, the Committee has dealt with five requests, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
At the moment, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful," Mikulka adds.
The success of Australia, which is the first to have significantly expanded its underwater possessions, has recently seen a global impact.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, which was allocated to it by the commission last week, corresponds to 1.6 million square kilometers, which is the extent of the country multiplied by six.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in exploration.
The future benefits of the exploitation of the seabed will be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will, in turn, make their request.
They can do so within ten years of ratifying the Montego Bay Convention.
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the zone of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There, no state enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this area shall be granted by an international institution established by convention.
"Nevertheless, let's not be mistaken, the seabed is not a Klondike," said Director Mikulka, exaggerating that "its areas are precisely clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract".
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed now also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern bloc within the framework of the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, the Convention, along with investors from a few other states, obtained the status of a so-called "pioneer investor".
It has the right to be extracted in the ClarionClipperton area in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The bottom is busy, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
