The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan took inspiration, this time, from nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center made this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan safety shield.
This robot will allow the brand’s vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that closely resembles the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the eyes composed of the bee, able to see at an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed a so-called laser range finder.
It detects obstacles that are located over a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
“As soon as it detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and will immediately change direction by forking its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If that were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Laboratory of Movement and the project’s chief engineer.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted up or down, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
“Every second this device only needs to process information and act on that data.
It does not need to retain the intuitive information or logic of prior maneuvers, which is why it can run continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes.”
This represents the first car to develop new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology that will be introduced in standard cars in a decade after Nissan.
The robot runs on lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
