Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, was the third to put to the vote a draft new constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results of 80% of the vote.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were zero and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft constitution to be adopted, he had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted outside the polling stations and a countdown by a non-governmental organization announced a large "yes" victory, between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed the victory of his draft constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
The “Constitution overwhelmingly triumphed,” he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the seat of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place in calm according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was about a text in 444 points consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft constitution enshrined the power of the state over the economy, reserving it the "development planning" of a country living mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Supported by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants strengthened powers to the head of state, who can hold up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the opportunity to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and run for a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution further consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
All 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched an assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were taken back safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at about 3:30 p.m. aboard a special aircraft at the al-Maza military base, attached to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to the Maadi Hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examinations.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been dumped from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organizer of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 Special Forces personnel, two helicopters on board, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire has occurred, and half of the kidnappers have been killed, the others fleeing," the official said.
He said 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit had been sent to the Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result through the professionalism and efficiency of our Secret Service, Special Forces men," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted during a patrol a 4x4 vehicle in which the kidnappers were on board, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed they were linked to a rebel group from Darfur, the Sudan-United Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
