Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states are assisting the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European bank in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it. The three countries support, in the amount of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also owning interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourgish and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, on this case, also appealing to the European Central Bank and the European Commission's Competition Officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis amplifying in more than a year is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be made in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (up to 49%) of the capital of the bank located in each of the countries.
The bank is undoubtedly going to sell part of its stakes, including primarily the principal insurance business acquired last year by the Dutch company ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis stocks began a dizzying fall, and in the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company’s shares fell 12 percent to their lowest level of 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the present value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company's leaders, is not realistic.
The company's management accuses the uncertainty overseas, in connection with the adoption of the $700 billion U.S. bailout plan, of being behind the downfall of Fortis shares.
On Monday, papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank’s customer circle and no agency was assaulted.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes that link the use of information regarding the prescription of medicines, in any case, to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it's like entrusting a fox to his chicken coop," Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and capital insured in the event of damage depend on the health condition of the client, and if they consider the risk to be too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed an insurance contract with them after learning about the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily provides himself with pharmacies, data on the person's drug purchases in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, which disease the person suffers from and what his health condition is.
For example, if that person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, it refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately places them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some determine at the same time a risk coefficient, so there is not much left for the insurer to do other than paperwork. However, tiny problems may still arise.
Disadvantages of this program include the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is seen by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while others do not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of data. They must ask the patient for permission before collecting necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been sanctioned for their failures in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing laboratory test results and linking them to drug use data to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to data, and controlling usage is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on expanding the circle of authority over data-providing companies is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not sufficient and therefore he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data on the sole consent of the data subject.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent or not, since if he or she refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
Thus, in the end, the hens depend on the kindness of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India have doubled their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global, issues.
Today there will also be a France-India summit where cooperation in the field of atomic energy will be discussed above all.
The European Union recognizes that India is an emerging major democratic power that should be given a broader right of speech in international affairs, but the member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support for New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They also did not go too far on this issue yesterday at this 9th summit held in Marseille.
The French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Prime Minister of India, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years, they were going to double the trade, which means an increase of a good hundred billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods increased from $25 billion to $55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious objective.
In this sense, they have legally harmonised the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civilian flights, and in this way, air trade can also grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with on the one hand India, which is the EU's leading trading partner, and on the other hand New Delhi, which is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit focused its attention on global affairs.
The Afghan and Pakistani situation was strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on this subject was raised.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both have a large part in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains true to the energy and climate agenda, notably that it would like to reduce its releases of toxic materials by at least 20 percent by 2020.
India also agreed on this, as well as on the need for a global market at the climate conference next year, and a reduction in greenhouse gas emissions by fifty percent by 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is now visiting the French capital, where during a bilateral meeting, he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the news agency, the deal would last for 15 years.
