Found the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fosset, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one that Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared."
The sheriff said no human remains were found on or near the plane.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (Ntsb) said that a few hours after the wreck was spotted, an investigative team sent to the site identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal belongings were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents named Fosset, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
At the sixth attempt, he had become in 2002, the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had travelled the world by plane and non-stop.
Among all these records, also the one to have flown at 15,445 meters in height, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertising you're not expecting.
An unusual 4x4 with an original and well-defined design, with marked lines, wide surfaces and sharp angles.
This is, in summary, Glk, the latest off road "compact" of the house of the star, with which Mercedes-Benz tried to give a wind of newness in this sector.
Thanks to its unusual, unexpected and unconventional content, the communication will accompany the launch of the 4x4 Glk, which will be available in Mercedes-Benz showrooms from October 17th.
Thus the hype that will accompany the start of the new car will give rise to an unprecedented mode of communication, through a futuristic campaign of 3D displays, used for the first time in Italy by an automobile brand.
A project of maxi displays, articulated in three different phases, that will dominate the heart of Milan’s shopping, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication provides for the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision, and thanks to special glasses distributed around Corso Como, it will be possible to see the new 4x4 in almost real dimensions and in three-dimensional format.
Indeed, you will have the impression that when looking at the image, the auto comes out of the poster.
Then, through the use of innovative Elimin8 technology, the new Glk will be illuminated according to the spots, in all its details, and then recomposed into a single image.
It is obvious that with this advertising, Mercedes is trying to introduce something new in the stereotypical field of automotive communication.
Will it succeed with this formula to attract the interest of future buyers? We will see.
